click on pics or read the thread

1096436671489474561.text:
10. Help and documentation

Even though it’s better if the system can be used without documentation, it may be necessary to provide help. Any such information should be easy to search, focused on the user's task, list concrete steps to be carried out, and not be too large.

1096436669966880768.text:
9. Help users recognize, diagnose, and recover from errors

Error messages should be expressed in plain language (no codes), precisely indicate the problem, and constructively suggest a solution.

Deep Dive:https://www.nngroup.com/articles/error-message-guidelines/ …

1096436668456873984.text:
8. Aesthetic and minimalist design
Dialogues should not contain information which is irrelevant or rarely needed. Every extra unit of information in a dialogue competes with the relevant units of information and diminishes their relative visibility.

1096436666573746176.text:
7. Flexibility and efficiency of use

Accelerators — unseen by the novice user — may often speed up the interaction for the expert user such that the system can cater to both inexperienced and experienced users. Allow users to tailor frequent actions.

1096436664778584064.text:
6. Recognition rather than recall

Minimize user memory load by making actions/options visible. Users shouldn’t have to recall info from one screen to another. Instructions for use of the system should be visible or easily retrievable.

Deep Dive:https://www.nngroup.com/articles/recognition-and-recall/ …

1096436663105007617.text:
5. Error prevention

Careful design which prevents a problem from occurring in the first place is > errors. Either eliminate error-prone conditions or check for them and present users with a confirmation option before they commit to the action.

Deep Dive:https://www.nngroup.com/articles/slips/

1096436660005421063.text:
4. Consistency and standards

Users should not have to wonder whether different words, situations, or actions mean the same thing.

Deep Dive: https://www.nngroup.com/articles/do-interface-standards-stifle-design-creativity/ …pic.twitter.com/vJWphUDZHi

1096436653831454721.text:
3. User control and freedom

Users often choose system functions by mistake and will need a clearly marked "emergency exit" to leave the unwanted state without having to go through an extended dialogue. Support undo and redo.

1096436652602478594.text:
2. Match between system and the real world

The system should speak users' language with phrases and concepts familiar to the user, rather than system-oriented terms. Follow real-world conventions, making information appear in a natural order.

Deep dive:https://www.nngroup.com/articles/match-system-real-world/ …

1096436651159666688.text:
1. Visibility of system status

The system should always keep users informed about what is going on, through appropriate feedback within reasonable time.

Deep Dive:https://www.nngroup.com/articles/visibility-system-status/ …
